Investigation Overview¶

Decision-making is core to planning, which forms the essence of this presentation as the basis in supporting decisions for management in the financial or banking sector. Given that loans forms a core aspect in the world, with businesses and individuals using loans as the foundation in meeting their goals, this presentation examines core variables to help in decision-making. Secondly, the presentation gives a deeper overview of core variables, and their relationship as core for management decisions. As a Summary Findings, of the examined LoanStatus, the majority of borrowers have 'Current' loan status, followed by Completed, while on Original Loan Amount across most borrowers were 4000, 15000, 12407, 100000, 5000 and 2000. Top 4 borrowers are Porfessional, Computer Programmer, Executive and Teachers. Lastly, Of some of the core 5 variables examined in multivariate analysis, LoanOriginalAmount has negative correlation with BorrowerRate (-0.33), EstimatedLoss (-0.43), EstimatedReturn (-0.29). BorrowerRate has positive correlation with EstimatedLoss (0.95), EstimatedReturn (0.82), and negative for LoanOriginalAmount (-0.33).

Loan Status¶

Loan Status formed a core variable in the ProsperDataset, hence a need to examine the distribution across loan listings. Based on the original data, loan status is divided into 12 groupings of Completed, Current, Charged Off, Defaulted, In progress and 7 Past Due categorization. By visualizing the Loan Status, it helps infer how the borrowers are distributed to support decisions. From visualization below, most loans have the completed status, with in progress and cancelled as the least levels.

Borrower Rate¶

Borrower Rate (Interest rate) is core in loans, and hence useful to show the most impactful rates for the different borrowers. The goal was in deciphering the distribution of BorrowerRate in the Loan Data, and explain the most utilized BorrowerRate across all loans in the ProsperLoanData. Based on the findings, for all sampled loans, there was an Outlier rate of 0.35 that was much applied higher than other loans. Overall, the histogram's peak rate was at 0.5, with comon range at 0.1 - 0.2

Income Range¶

Getting loans is affected by multiple factors, which made examining Incomes and Ranges of the borrowers essential for decision-making. The goal was to decipher the most Income Ranges engaged in Accessing the Prosper Loans and how the data distributed across borrower's income ranges. Based on the visualization below, most borrowers are in 25,000-49,999 totalling 32,192 members. However, this proportion is not too far from second group. Next, the second group lie in the 50,000-74,999 with 31050 and in third place 100,000+ with 17337. As management, customizing marketing operations based on this findings is core.

Employment Status and Loan Status¶

Doing bivariate comparison assists make decisions based on two variables, of which examining Employment Status and Loan Status can help make proper management choices, loan planning and marketing decisions. The goal was to show which groupings have the most impact across the member's loans based on employment and loan status. Based on the visualization below, some findings are:

  • The most impactful grouping in the dataset is the current, which has the bar with the highest peak for Employed
  • The Employed group has the most current loan status, with other groupings in the same category with very minute levels
  • In the Completed status, those with Full-time have the highest bar, thus making the most contribution in this group The same impact is seen in Charged Off, and Defaulted who also have the highest level among the Full-Time members.

Loan Status and Borrower Rate¶

As for banking institutions, earning profit is core, and interest rate is one useful aspect in making this possible. Thus, Loan Status and Borrowers were compared in bivariate analysis. Using the visualization below, the box plots show a relationship between Loan Status and Interest Rates. On checking the median line on the box plots, Charged Off, Defaulted and Past Due loans have the highest BorrowerRate. Correlation Between Continuous Variables¶

In the ideal business world, different issues and factors impacts on decisions, which makes the examination of multiple variables essential in improving the decision process. For managers in financial and banking organizations, examining correlation in the Prosper Data based on the variables 'LoanOriginalAmount', 'BorrowerRate', 'Occupation', 'EstimatedReturn', 'EstimatedLoss' helps give a better overview of the association and make decisions on the most import relationships. The findings in the visualization below shows that of the 5 variables, LoanOriginalAmount has negative correlation with BorrowerRate (-0.33), EstimatedLoss (- 0.43), EstimatedReturn (-0.29). Secondly, BorrowerRate (Interest Rate) has positive correlation with EstimatedLoss (0.95), EstimatedReturn (0.82), and negative for LoanOriginalAmount (-0.33).
